Is there a difference between these two:

∃x∈N.(x∈B)→(x∈A)

∃x∈N.(x∈B)∧(x∈A)

Yes! The first one, ∃x∈N.(x∈B)→(x∈A), means that there exists an x in the natural numbers, where if x is in the set B, it must also be in the set A. This means x could not be in B, in which case x may or may not also be in A, and the statement would hold true, OR x is in B and in A. The second, ∃x∈N.(x∈B)∧(x∈A), means that x is in both the set A and B! This is different from the first one, as the first one will be true even if x is in A but not B, or if x is in neither.

Does anyone remember the difference between entailment and implied?
f(x) and f(y) are both members of the codomain (they're both the same member, in fact) but x is equal to y and this doesn't violate the definition of a function

implies is a logical operator, so it can return either true or false. entails, on the other hand, is metalogic, so it acts as a *statement*. it doesn't evaluate to anything (although it can be valid or invalid)
in other words, implies is like asking a question, and entails is like stating a fact
the fact can be incorrect, but it doesn't "return" an answer

It would not. This is actually a pretty interesting case.  Antisymmetry states that if (aRb and bRa), then (a = b).  However, when we say a = b, we are making a claim about identity.  We are saying that a is identical to b, though because we use the equal sign, we might be inclined to think that it means the same thing as equivalence but it is not.  For example: (a ^ b) and not(not(a) or not(b)) are logically equivalent so the equivalence relation would hold for them, but they are not identical and so thus, (a ^ b) != not(not(a) or not(b)).  Do not think of equivalence (R in the case of aRb and bRa) as being "=".  "=" means identical, equivalence means more of equal in value.  If R were to be "=", then we would have a tautology because (a = b ^ b=a) -> a=b will always be true.

Lol I got wayyy too invested in this question but I would say no.  If A and B are logically contradictory statements, then that means that all possible combinations of truth values (think of a truth table) we use for the propositions in (A ^ B) will always result in False.  A and B are made up of atomic propositions that should be able to take on any truth value and still evaluate to False.  This means that if A is false, B doesn't necessarily need to be true.  What really bugged me about this question is that it essentially asks whether A and B needed to force the truth value of the other (ie. if A is false, does B have to be true).   After some web searches and LLM probing, I think I can comfortably say that A and B are independent propositions that can take on whatever truth value they want.  For example, here's an interesting case, let A be the proposition P, and B be the statement (Q and not(Q)).  If A were to be false, it could not force B to be true regardless of the truth values (since B is a contradiction).  Given any combination of truth values for P and Q, the statement would still be false.  Therefore, A and B are logically contradictory.  It's definitely a very weird case and it probably shouldn't concern you that much.  Contradictions can generally just be thought of as violations of the law of noncontradiction (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Law_of_noncontradiction) and will generally just come in the form of A and not(A), where A is some claim/proposition.

could someone explain this part of problem 5 on the first test? I dont really get the explanation provided on the key

Sure! So, in this part of the problem, three conditions hold:

(1) A ⊂ B
(2) ¬(B ⊆ D)
(3) ¬(D ⊂ B)

When solving problems like these, I also find diagrams helpful. Here's how you might visualize the above conditions:

Let's start with (1). For this condition to hold, A must be a subset of B without being identical to B. In the above we have two situations where that's true, so (1) holds in both of those cases (the left and right parts of the figure). What about (2)? In order for B to *not* be an improper subset of D, we can have one of two situations. Either B can be completely disjoint from D (represented by the leftmost part of the figure), or B and D can share some overlap but have some different elements (represented by the rightmost part of the figure). So, in the above diagram, we have all our scenarios under which (2) is true. Furthermore, (1) is true in each of these scenarios as well. What about (3)? Well, for D to *not* be a proper subset of B, it's enough for D and B to either be disjoint or to again share some different elements. In the left and right halves of the diagram then, (3) holds as well. So that's the space we're working with in this problem.

Now, we know that H = A ∩ D. If we're in the leftmost scenario, then that gives us the empty set {}, so H can be empty. Does it always have to be empty though? Well, I didn't do a very good job drawing it but imagine scooting A in the rightmost part of the dialogue so that it's just touching the orange spot between B and D. That would make A have common elements with D and would make their intersection non-empty, making H non-empty. So, the best answer to the problem is "Could be empty." If D is disjoint from B, then H is empty. If D shares elements with A, then H is non-empty. Hope that helps!

When the set of counterexamples (C) is empty, it means that there are no instances where the predicate P(x) is false within our domain of natural numbers. 

Since there are no counterexamples, it should then follow that the implication P(x) -> P(x-1) holds true for every instance of when a positive Integer is plugged in. If there were any natural number for which this implication failed, it would be included in the set of counterexamples (C), contradicting the initial assumption that C is empty.

If we trying looking at this from the other direction, (aka B |= A), it's possible that we could be in a situation where false -> false == true, meaning there WOULD be an element in our set of counter examples, so C could not be the empty set.

for the fundamental theorom of the arithmatic, do both sides need to have the same prime factors with the same multiples? Or just the prime factors themselves? Ie. is 2 * 3 = 2 * 3^2 correct or does it back to be exact.. 2 * 3^2 = 2 * 3^2
Also, can someone please explain this proof, specifically the highlighted part? I understand when we prove irrational numbers for other instances, but the multiplicity part of this one is confusing.

The fundamental theorem of arithmetic states that every positive integer greater than 1 can be represented by a unique prime factorization, meaning that each unique number differs by prime factors and/or their multiples.  For a number to be equal, they should have the exact same prime factorization (both in terms of the prime factors and their multiples).  When we usually do proof by contradictions (for example, to show that a number not rational), we can often reach a contradiction usually by talking about the multiplicities of prime factors because by the mere fact that one side of the equality must differ in the number of multiples of a certain prime factor  (e.g., a specific factor might always be even on one side, and odd on the other), we reach a contradiction because they can't possibly be the same number (thus a contradiction becauase we asserted they were equal).

From the left side, we know that *a* on the right side must contain a prime factor of 3 in order to be equal (by the FTOA).  However, the multiplicities of 3 on both sides of the equation can never be equal. On the left side, however, we know that we must have either 1 as a multiplicity of 3 or 1 more than a multiple of 3 as a multiplicity of 3 (in the event that 3 is a factor of b) since 3^1 x b^3, where b has some factor 3 of multiplicity *n* is 3^(1+3*n*).

The set builder { {x, y} | x ∈ S and y ∈ S and x = y } creates a set where x = y and both are elements of set S. In a set, duplicates are not allowed, so {x, y} where x = y collapses down to a single element.

In an example case where S = {1,2,3} (giving us a cardinality of 3), the set builder would generate {{1},{2},{3}} because each {x, y} where x = y collapses to a single element set.

So the cardinality of this set would also be 3.

I can explain why (8! - 14 x 6!) is an answer! There are multiple ways to solve this problem, but I like this one:

In this approach, you subtract the number of ways they can sit next to each other (14 x 6!) from the total ways to sit the group (8!).

First, to we know there are 8! ways to seat, or permute, the whole group.

Next, we need the number of ways the enemies can sit next to each other.
- The other six can be ordered in any way (6! possibilities)
- For each permutation of the others, there are seven places to set the pair in between/on the end of the group (7 possibilites)
- For each location, there are two ways to order the pair itself (2! or 2 possibilities) 

Multiplied together, the totally number of ways the pair can sit together is (6! x 14). Thus, there are (8! - 6! x 14) ways to order the group while keeping the enemies separated.
